The paper proposes a novel multiple access scheme for machine-to-machine (M2M) communications, which involves optimizing the probabilistic transmission of M2M devices based on their individual delay requirements. This involves addressing issues related to congestion and access delay in M2M systems with a large number of devices. Given the focus on communication protocols and network optimization, the most likely sub-categories are cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also deals with system-level optimization and control, which could place it in the cs.SY (Systems and Control) category. Additionally, the paper deals with M2M communications, which could place it in the cs.MM (Multimedia) category. Finally, the paper deals with random access techniques, which could place it in the cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) category.
